article.description:
The Minnesota Timberwolves have made their
home arena one of the league's most inhospitable for visiting
teams.
article.headline: Garnett, Szczerbiak are too tough for Knicks
article.linkText: T-Wolves hold off Knicks for 17th straight home win
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Minnesota Timberwolves have made their home arena one of the league's most inhospitable for visiting teams.
Garnett

Kevin Garnett had 22 points, 16 rebounds and nine assists, and Wally Szczerbiak added 26 points and 11 rebounds as the Timberwolves defeated the New York Knicks 99-90 Sunday for their 17th straight win at Target Center. Minnesota, which has won seven straight overall, improved to 27-5 (.844) at home. Only the Indiana Pacers (25-4, .862) have a better record. "I feel like if we come out and do the things we're supposed to do, we're supposed to win,'' said Garnett, who fell one assist short of a triple-double for the second straight game. The Timberwolves have won 22 of their last 27 games overall to challenge Portland for the No. 4 spot in the Western Conference. If they hold that position, the Wolves have a good chance of getting out of the first round of the playoffs, something they failed to do the past six years. "I was worried about the second half of the season coming out of the All-Star Game, so I told the guys that wherever you go, be thinking about the same thing,'' Garnett said. "I can truly say that we're totally focused.'' The Wolves begin a crucial five-game road trip Tuesday in Seattle. "We've got to get that home-court advantage,'' Szczerbiak said. "The way we're playing at home, that's going to be big. If we slide to the fifth spot, we're going to be underdogs again.'' Allan Houston scored 21 of his 34 points in the fourth quarter for the Knicks, including four 3-pointers. His hot shooting helped New York whittle a 29-point first-half deficit to as little as four. The Knicks, who have lost six straight on the road, are 4{ games behind the Washington Wizards for the eighth and final spot in the Eastern Conference. The Wolves broke the game open early by shooting 57 percent in the first half, compared with 24 percent for the Knicks. Minnesota reached its biggest lead by outscoring New York 52-21 after the Knicks took their only lead of the game at 4-2. "I'm speechless right now. We've done this before,'' New York coach Don Chaney said of his team's first-half struggles. It was the Wolves' turn to go cold in the second half. Minnesota made only 12 of 34 shots in the second half and allowed the Knicks to chip away at the lead. The Wolves led by 20 after three quarters and by 14 with 4:40 to play, but Houston hit a 3-pointer with 1:47 left to pull New York to 86-80. Anthony Peeler's first basket, a 3-pointer with 1:33 left, restored a nine-point lead, but Houston answered with a 3 of his own to make it 89-83 with 51 seconds left. He made a conventional three-point play with 33.5 seconds left to bring New York within four. The Wolves made eight of 10 free throws to seal the game in the final minute. "We let our lack of offense get us down,'' Houston said. "And you just can't depend on your jump shot.'' Latrell Sprewell shot just 2-for-14, and the Knicks made only four of their first 25 shots. Game notes
Wolves coach Flip Saunders said guard Rod Strickland and forward Joe Smith would accompany the team on its upcoming road trip. Strickland has missed 15 games because of a groin strain, while Smith has missed 13 with a sprained ankle. Saunders said it was possible that both might be ready near the end of the trip. ... Minnesota plays 12 of its final 21 games on the road. ... The seven-game winning streak is the third-longest in Wolves' history. ... Aside from Clarence Weatherspoon's 10 points on 4-for-7 shooting, the Knicks shot 5-of-31 in the first half.
